                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "At what time of day does the nurse recommend that a child prescribed methylphenidate be given the last dose of the day of the medication?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nMethylphenidate is used to treat attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder and has stimulant effects. Children with attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder would take the morning dose after breakfast, and the last daily dose needs to be taken at least 6 hours before bedtime (14 hours for extended-release forms) to prevent insomnia. Usually the primary health care provider recommends that the last dose be given just before the noontime meal. The other options are incorrect.\n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Generate Solutions\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Psychiatric: Attention-Deficit-Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) Agents\nHealth Problem: Mental Health: Neurodevelopmental Disorders\nIntegrated Process: Teaching and Learning\nPriority Concepts: Mood and Affect, Patient Education\nStrategies: Comparable or Alike Options, Subject\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nFocus on the subject, last dose of the day of methylphenidate. Eliminate options 1 and 2 because they are comparable or alike. Recalling that this medication is a stimulant and focusing on the subject will direct you to the correct option. Remember that it is best to administer it shortly before the noontime meal.\n ",
                        "id": "e6eb443ad1a0431981292ab5a09aa111",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
